__NOTOC__
{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}
[[File:Bungaroosh at Prince's Crescent, Round Hill, Brighton.JPG|thumb|right|Close-up of a bungaroosh wall in the [[Round Hill, Brighton|Round Hill]] area of Brighton]]
'''Bungaroosh''' (also spelt '''bungeroosh''',<ref name="NEB11">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=11.}}</ref> '''bungarouche''',<ref name="NHLE-1415924">{{NHLE|num=1415924|desc=15 North Street and attached brick paving to yard or twitten, Brighton|accessdate=27 September 2013}}</ref> '''bungarooge''', '''bunglarooge''',<ref name="Antram6">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=6.}}</ref> '''bunglarouge'''<ref name="Context29">{{Cite journal|last=Fraser |first=Rob |date=March 1991 |title=Bungaroosh (Bungarouche, Bunglarouge?) |journal=Context |publisher=Institute of Historic Building Conservation (IHBC) |location=Tunbridge Wells |issue=29 |page=7 |url=http://www.ihbc.org.uk/context_archive/29/bungaroosh_dir/bungaroosh_s.htm |accessdate=27 December 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6DEPEbtMM?url=http://www.ihbc.org.uk/context_archive/29/bungaroosh_dir/bungaroosh_s.htm |archivedate=27 December 2012 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> and other variations) is a [[Composite material|composite building material]] used almost exclusively in the English [[seaside resort]] of [[Brighton]] and its attached neighbour Hove between the mid-18th and late 19th centuries, when it grew from a fishing village into a large town.<ref name="Antram6"/>  Bungaroosh is often found in buildings of that era in the town and in its near neighbours Worthing and [[Lewes]],<ref name="LewesCAA20">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/plan_CAA_Lewespages15to28.pdf |title=Lewes Conservation Area Character Appraisal |date=April 2007 |format=PDF |publisher=Lewes District Council |page=20 |accessdate=21 February 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EbY90nZA?url=http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/plan_CAA_Lewespages15to28.pdf |archivedate=21 February 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> but is little known elsewhere.<ref name="Antram6"/>  In this respect, it is similar to [[mathematical tile]]s - another localised building material introduced in, and characteristic of, that era.<ref name="Antram6"/><ref name="LewesCAA20"/>  It can incorporate any of a wide variety of substances and materials, and is used most often in external walls.<ref name="NEB11"/><ref name="Antram7">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=7.}}</ref>

The manufacture of bungaroosh involved placing miscellaneous materials, such as whole or broken bricks, cobblestones, [[flint]]s (commonly found on the [[South Downs]] around Brighton), small pebbles, sand and pieces of wood into [[hydraulic lime]] and then pouring it between [[Formwork|shuttering]] until it has set.<ref name="Context29"/><ref name="Antram7"/>  The shuttering (formwork) process typically involved erecting a wooden frame (often made out of [[Railroad tie|railway sleepers]] after they became readily available in the 19th century), pouring in the lime and adding solid materials to the mixture.  Other structural fittings, such as brick [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] or wooden [[Lintel (architecture)|lintel]]s, could then be added if more support was needed or other structures were to be added.<ref name="Context29"/>  This was particularly common in Brighton, where bungaroosh walls were often built behind the impressive [[stucco]]ed façades of [[Regency architecture|Regency-style houses]].<ref name="Context29"/><ref name="Antram7"/> The material is particularly prevalent in the early 19th-century squares, crescents and terraces of Brighton's seafront,<ref name="LewesCAA24">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/plan_CAA_Lewespages15to28.pdf |title=Lewes Conservation Area Character Appraisal |date=April 2007 |format=PDF |publisher=Lewes District Council |page=24 |accessdate=21 February 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6EbY90nZA?url=http://www.lewes.gov.uk/Files/plan_CAA_Lewespages15to28.pdf |archivedate=21 February 2013 |deadurl=no |df=dmy }}</ref> such as [[Regency Square, Brighton|Regency Square]], [[Royal Crescent, Brighton|Royal Crescent]] and the [[Kemp Town]] estate.  Another technique was to wait for the mixture to set, then render it with a lime-based mixture and paint it.  This produced a consistent, regular surface which could be used to build the symmetrical façades required in [[Georgian architecture|Georgian architecture -]] a popular style in Lewes.<ref name="LewesCAA24"/>

Although the material is solid once set, it has poor resistance to water.  If it dries out completely, it can crumble away; but if it gets wet it can dissolve and start to move, causing structural failure.  Regular drying-out and saturation caused by the effects of the weather has caused some [[Bay window|bay-window fronts]] to collapse in Brighton.<ref name="Context29"/>  A common maxim states that much of Brighton "could be demolished with a well-aimed hose"; the supposed extent of this destruction varies between "a third" and "half" depending on the source.<ref name="Context29"/><ref name="Antram7"/>

The [[etymology]] of the first part of the word is the same as bungalow; late 17th century: from Hindi ''baṅglā'' ‘belonging to Bengal’. Second part is unknown, possibly a colloquialism.

