'''Freighting''' refers to the hauling of [[cargo]], historically, using a [[dog]] team to [[mushing|mush]] goods cross-country. During the [[Gold rush#North America|North American gold rushes]], such as the [[Klondike Gold Rush]], dogs were valuable [[draft animal]]s, going where [[horse]]s could not and withstanding harsher [[weather]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wm9dCAAAQBAJ&pg=PT148|title=The Draft Dog - Past and Present|last=Lavigne|first=Guillaume de|date=2015-03-18|publisher=Lulu Press, Inc|year=|isbn=9781326218447|location=|pages=148|language=en}}</ref>

Dog teams were commonly used for [[transportation]] and in [[Canada]] and [[Alaska]] were used to [[Mail delivery by animal|deliver the mail]] during the winter. Large teams of sturdy dogs were required to haul the heavy loads. With the advent of [[air mail]] in the 1920s, mail delivery by dog team became outmoded, and gradually the mail runs became fewer until the last regular mail freighting route in Canada was shut down in the 1960s and in 1963 in the United States.

The dog sport of [[weight pulling]] is a modern adaptation of freighting.<ref name=":0" />

