{{Infobox power station | name = Montalto di Castro | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Italy | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = | coordinates = {{coord|42|21|36|N|11|31|19|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = [[Italy]] | location = [[Montalto di Castro]] | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = November 2009, December 2010 | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = | operator = | solar_type = PV | ps_units_operational = 276,156 | solar_site_area = {{convert|166|ha|km2|1|abbr=on}} | ps_electrical_capacity = 84.23&nbsp;[[Megawatt|MW]]<sub>p</sub><ref name=exen>[http://www.exenewable.com/projectProfile.asp?id=12563 eXenewable Project Profile Page - Monalto di Castro, PV, Italy]</ref> | ps_electrical_cap_fac = 19% | ps_annual_generation = 140 [[GWh]] | website = | extra = }}
The '''Montalto di Castro photovoltaic power station''' is a 84 [[megawatt]] (MW) [[photovoltaic power station]] at [[Montalto di Castro]] in [[Province of Viterbo|Viterbo province]], [[Italy]]. The project was developed by the independent developer SunRay that was later acquired by [[SunPower]]. The park is the largest PV project in Italy, and among [[List of photovoltaic power stations|the largest in Europe]].
The project was built in several phases. The first phase with a total capacity of 24&nbsp;MW<sub>AC</sub> was connected in late 2009. It uses SunPower solar panels as well as its tracker systems.<ref name=exen /> The second phase (8 MW) was commissioned in 2010, and the third and fourth phases, totaling 44&nbsp;MW<sub>AC</sub>, were completed in December 2010, totaling 276,156 [[solar module]]s with 305 watt each.<ref> [http://global.sunpowercorp.com/success-stories/?relType=SP_Content_C&relID=1293993963620 SunPower Builds the Largest Solar Power Plant in the World] </ref>
In December 2010 SunPower has completed the sale of Montalto di Castro solar park to a consortium of international investors. SunPower designed and built the solar power plant and will provide ongoing operations and maintenance services for the new owners.<ref>[http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases-test/sunpower-completes-sale-of-44-megawatt-montalto-di-castro-solar-park-112493369.html SunPower Completes Sale of 44-Megawatt Montalto di Castro Solar Park]</ref>
